sses practices of collecting in archiveological film and rereads films by Joseph Cornell and Rania Stephan to explore an archival practice that dislocates and relocates the female image in film. In so doing, she not only shows how Benjamin's work is as relevant to film theory as ever; she shows how archiveology can awaken artists and audiences to critical forms of history and memory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aArchives. 0aFilm archives. 0aMotion picture film. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aIAMHIST prize winners.  aMichael Nelson Prize.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106963320 cprintz978082237045140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822372004423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822372004/original  a978-3-11-069633-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles